< Text>
In these parts, the main option is Vitality Bowls.  However while that's a decent option, I prefer Bowl Of Heaven.  My go-to order is a regular North Shore with 22g of added vanilla protein.  The Sea Sider and Sunset are good options, too.

Service is always fantastic, but parking can be crazy during peak times (don't forget to check around the corner, but those spots can be a little narrow).</Text>

<Text>Visited twice just to check out how it compares to Vitality Bowls. Comparable bowl & smoothie offerings, but no savory options. Presentation is not as pretty, but it is a few dollars cheaper. Pay close attention to which ingredients are blended and which are toppings (i.e. strawberries blended, but chia seeds offered as a topping). Potential to be awesome if you specify exactly how you want your bowl prepared. Didn't work for me on auto pilot. Might give them another chance, but not certain.</Text>< Rate>

< review>
I went into the shop to get the service records on a car I bought. I was told all records were wiped clean in November 2017 by accident.  Next I went on carfax, guess what- Menifee Transmission never reports to car fax.  How do you not spend  $20 on a flash drive to keep a copy of your records safe? Find a shop with better business practices.< /review>
< user_id>
108371927680044885223< /user_id>
<Resp>{'time': 1549069078331, 'text': "Unfortunately, our hard drive was wiped and we have since made changes to ensure it doesn't happen again, and it is not as simple and cheap as a $20 flash drive, our database is much more complicated then that.  However, I would like to mention that auto repair shops have never been required to report to Carfax.  From a quick look at Carfax's website it seems that auto repair facilities can pay a premium to Carfax and become an authorized shop, these shops more then likely, report the maintenance.  Reporting to Carfax is not required or mandatory, it is only an advertising option for auto repair facilities to get exposure and customers.  I would also like to add, when buying a used vehicle you should request copies of all service records from the seller and if they cannot provide them then you ask them to obtain such records prior to the purchase.  Used vehicles are normally buyer beware and sold as is. Also, even if our system had not been damaged, we would not have provided those records to you unless we had permission from the individual who owned the car previously, otherwise it is a violation of privacy.  I hope you have a good day."}<//Resp><Rating>1</Rating>< user_name>

Great neighborhood joint

Great service

Good people

Forget parking take an Uber or walk here you'll have more fun that way.

Has record store inside.

Great place for live music showcasing small independent musical acts.

Good selection of beer and liquors.

Giant Patio out back

Great place to hang out late after all the restaurants have closed in downtown San Pedro.

A true must see.

Has food offerings on the patio

I always have a good time Everytime I visit.<//Text>

< text>
Today was my first time eating at this location and I will say I was a disappointed in the service . First off our server was quick to take our drink order but after that it became slow . My chicken tortilla soup had no chicken :-( Secondly ,  we had to constantly keep an eye out for our waitress in order to ask for anything and when we did it took about 20 minutes to receive it . Lastly, when we decided we wanted to pay , we had to wait 25/30 minutes to pay . It was not crowded at all yet the service wasn‚Äôt what it should be . The entree we received were hot so that‚Äôs why I came them an additional star. I felt as though I had to serve myself . If we needed refills we had to play hide and seek with our server. She rarely came to check on how we were doing . Lastly , as we went to pay check finally they overcharged me and then tried to fix it by paying another groups check. I am shocked that a manager would allow such bad service to be okay.Overall, I would not recommend this location to eat at unless you have 3 hours to eat food.<//text>

<user_id>101518931921001333543< /user_id><name>Bryan Duncan<//name>< text>
Worse service I have ever had.  Took 10 minutes for the waitress to take a drink order.  I ordered a 3 Combo meal. 2 cheese enchiladas and a taco. <userid>102918253898437847981</userid>< Time>
1475249636301< /Time>
<resp>None</resp>< Pics>
None< /Pics>
<Rating>4<//Rating><review>BIRTHDAY MONTH=BIRTHDAY COUPONS=HAPPY RODNEY

Free entree (up to $12.99) for email club members

Seeing how the El Torito in Cerritos closed down, the next closest location to me is at the Long Beach Town Centre.  Eagerly awaiting redeeming my birthday month email, I hopped on the freeway, turned on the first exit, and parked in the front of TGI Friday's.  A leisurely stroll in front of Edwards Cinema, and I found myself at El Torito.

Being the first customer of the day, I found myself salsa/cumbia/bachata dancing to the rousing music while waiting to be seated.  A gentleman led me to the 10 person booths by the windows, facing Chik-Fil-A & In N' Out.  Being 1 person in a 10 person booth made me feel like "El Jefe".

Complimentary chips & salsa started my lunch.  The salsa had some heat to it, but not enough to put off those that can't handle spicy.

Grilled chicken taco salad-
Romain lettuce, grilled chicken, refried beans, cotija cheese, roasted pepitas, crisp tortilla strips, pico de gallo,   guacamole, sour cream & avocado dressing (on the side) in a large taco shell.  Huge portions in an oversized plate, the taco salad did not fail to impress.  The cubed chicken was tender, the guac & sour cream smooth, and the romaine crisp.  What helped add more substance to the dish were the refried beans underneath.  After a little mixing, along with a slathering of the avocado dressing, the grilled chicken taco salad proved quite the behemoth.  But, alas, it was no match for "El luchador gordo"!!  I stayed away from the taco shell, being I already had tortilla chips with salsa.

Service was excellent!  My attendant worked at the Cerritos location and a few other local El Toritos, previously.  He came by with more salsa and checked frequently to see if I needed anything.  He also refilled my soda water & lime 3 times, 1 for me to take home.  Seating is via tables & booths of varying sizes.  The cantina, with a more intimate dining area, is directly left of the entrance.  The main dining area is behind the entrance.  Being seated by the windows, I had plenty of indirect light around me as I ate.  Having a great complimentary lunch, enjoying a gorgeous day in SoCal, and I was a happy camper!

Parking is at the Long Beach Town Centre.  El Torito is located in the Promenade, with the closest parking being near Chik-Fil-A & In N' Out.

Whew, I am stuffed!  El Torito's grilled chicken taco salad was a hefty meal, all the more better being free when I showed my free birthday month email on my phone.  Service was top-notch, as I was attended to frequently.  Considering all that, plus a clean, cozy dining area & some killer music to rock out to, El Torito at the Long Beach Town Centre comes highly recommended by your's truly.

< Review>
They are known for their dipping ramen. Their menu is concise and easy to pick from. The service is great and the food was prepared quickly. They have outdoor sittings available.

-1 star because they didn't follow any protocol of taking temperature or hand sanitization. When you pay with cards, you still have to sign on their touchscreen devices (making it unsanitary as they don't clean it after each use).  -1 because I don't think there's anything unique about this place. The flavor is average, the noodle is standard, and overall, sitting right on the benchmark.

Expect to pay between $18-25 per person. I'll be trying nearby restaurants first before considering returning.<//Review>

<name>Tyler Nguyen</name><time>1620445319636<//time><rate>5<//rate><Text>Overview:
Did some research before coming here and decided to come to this location vs their annex location across the street.  Haven't had the annex location yet but very glad that we chose this one!  First off, can I just say that I appreciate a ramen shop that understands my late night ramen cravings and so they're open late?  We came here for second dinner at midnight and pretty much had the shop to ourselves.

Food:
I am a huge tsukemen fan so when I heard this place is known for their dipping ramen then I had to try it.  I immediately picked the cha siu tsukemen since it comes with the most food :P   The noodles were a great level of firmness, the chashu pork for tender, and the broth.... the broth was absolutely awesome and reminded me of some ramen shops I had in Japan.  I was really full afterwards!  To this day, I still day dream about it every now and then and plan to come back as soon as I can!< /Text><Pictures>None<//Pictures><resp>None</resp><Gmap_id>0x80c2bb74df48dd81:0xf5e9b108b806741f</Gmap_id></record></dataset><record>

<review>easily the best tsukemen you will find in SoCal, and probably a top contender for best tsukemen west of the Rockies.

fwiw, i only ever order the tsukemen when i come here. I'm sure their ramen is great, but the tsukemen is just that good.

the broth is velvety and sumptuous, the char siu is evanescently tender, and the noodles have a delightfully springy bite to them. squeeze the lime they give you over the noodles to add some brightness and acidity to cut through the richness.

the portion might seem small but a regular bowl of noodles and broth is a challenge for me (a fully grown man with a healthy appetite). with extra char siu (that is, in addition to the pieces already in the broth) and a seasoned egg, it's a veritable feast.

if you live in Southern California and like Asian food, you owe it to yourself to come here. undefeated.</review>< rating>
5</rating>

<user>109439349753132669234< /user><Name>Pi Ho<//Name><Time>1617040040487< /Time><Rate>4<//Rate>< text>
Went to this Noodle shop from recommendation from a you tube video.

This was our first time here and we wanted a nice hot bowel of noodles/ramen, because it was quite cool outside that evening.

We were so hungry and we both ordered Charlie tsukemen by mistake. The cold noodles were thick and delicious.  The slices of pork belly are amazing as well. The broth was a hot dipping broth in a separate bowl, also tasted good.

We both decided to dump the dipping sauce all over the noodles bowl to in order to avoid having to dip the noodles each time we took a bite to eat.

This combination was still good, but not what we wanted on the chilly evening.

Next time I am going to order the spicy ramen with level 3 heat.  That way I know we have ordered something served steaming hot.  The normal way we like or orders.

Going back soon!< /text>

<Date>1617774527989<//Date><name>Paul Roder<//name><rating>5<//rating>< review>
Excellent ambiance. Easy to find right on a well trafficked corner. Plenty of outdoor and indoor seating. Waitstaff was very friendly and accommodating of questions. Your entire party must be present in order to be seated due to covid rules so just be advised on that. Food was excellent and the drinks were standard fare for a nicer Japanese restaurant. Asahi and nigori sake were the orders in my group. The ramen was well prepared and the noodles had a good consistency and flavor to the broth. The pork was flavorful, tender and had a slightly smoky flavor which was VERY good. Extra noodles were quick to come out if you find you want more after you finish your initial bowl. Across the street is another Tsujita spot but we did not go over to investigate. Definitely would recommend a visit here. Side note, for parties over 4, splitting the bill can take a bit of time as it is pretty popular and waitstaff get busy.< /review>

<user_id>101894112267806111677<//user_id><text>One of my favorite spots for tsukemen ! I love coming here and it's definitely worth the wait. It often looks bad but the tables go in and out pretty quickly.

I would recommend getting their tsukemen upon visiting - I usually get it with the char siu and the boiled egg. They give you a huge bowl of noodles with a small bowl of thick thick delicious broth to dip your noodles in ! Be careful, it's quite salty to just be sipping on by itself.

How I usually like to eat it is with extra extra likes and if you like spicy, they have a jar of pickles greens that goes really well with the noodles. SO SO good.

Once you're done with the meal, feel free to ask them to thin out your tsukemen soup with some broth to end the meal.

10/10 would recommend. Although some people have said it may be a little salty, I think it's definitely worth trying.< /text></record></dataset><record>

<Review>I was really looking forward to this authentic experience that was talked up by family and friends. My experience was rather mixed. We went with a party of 4 and although the line was a decent wait, COVID times meant not too many others were fighting for tables. The outdoor seating was decent for the size of the place and the QR code menu was an interesting way to stay sanitary.
We all ordered the standard go-to tsukemen which others recommended. I can see now why this ramen isn‚Äôt for everyone. Yes, the noodles are rather cold, and the broth that you dip in is supposed to counter that, but the broth needed to be hotter to do so. The noodles and the pork were great. Pork chashu is supposed to be that salty so no complaints there. Noodles were clearly authentic and had great texture.
The broth was something else. If you are sensitive to fishy smell/taste then you should stay away. The tsukemen is not advertised as being a fish based broth, but it was truly reeking of some sea-based product. Think fish gravy. Cutting the flavor with the added limes or even with requested chili on the side did little to mitigate that taste. One of our party‚Äôs members took one bite and was immediately put off eating any further.
I‚Äôd like to say that it ended there, but sadly several of our party members also suffered massive stomach pains the following night/day. Japanese food has never done that to me before, authentic or otherwise. We went out of our way to try this recommendation, unfortunately I won‚Äôt be passing the recommendation along. Be careful of hype.<//Review>< rate>
3</rate>

< Date>
1544554737497< /Date>
< review>
JAPAN üáØüáµ
Eat the World LA review:
Not to be outdone by downtown's Little Tokyo, the small area on Sawtelle Blvd with many Japanese businesses became known as Little Osaka. This apparently rubbed the wrong way on the folks that were not specifically from Osaka and eventually the strip was rebranded as Sawtelle Japantown, a decidedly boring name.
¬∞
Anyone that loves Japanese food, and especially ramen, is supposed to come here for their famous tsukemen, tonkotsu broth that is simmered for a full 60 hours, sweetened and thickened by seafood. Tsukemen is served as components, you do the addition and subtraction yourself, usually dipping the noodles as you go. If you need more broth, it can be refilled. Ajitama tsukemen is broth with a seasoned soft boiled egg, it is also available plain or with char siu. After you finish your noodles, ask for them to pour in some light broth to the dipping sauce and enjoy the resulting soup on its own.
¬∞
The standard bowl of tonkotsu ramen is also available here for those that prefer everything at one time.</review>

<user_name>Michael Morrow</user_name><time>1557642981330<//time>< rate>
5< /rate>
<review>After having some at an amazing little shop in Shinjuku, Tokyo, I was really craving some tsukemen (dipping noodles) once I was back in the states. I found this place had it, so I made the drive from Phoenix this weekend to give it another try. I was worried it would be an Americanized version, but I think they got it just right. The dipping broth is rich and thick like I remember and the noodles were great. I was a little confused at the end since I remembered the shop in Tokyo having insulated pitchers of soup stock (dashi) spread along the counter for pouring into your leftover dipping broth to make it thinner and more like a drinkable soup, but there was no pitchers on the tables they had here, and instead I was directed to this little "tsukemen" sauce bottle on the table... When I rephrased it, they took my bowl up to the counter where I finally saw the same sort of insulated pitcher I remembered from Japan. Once I had the bowl back with the warm soup it was just as tasty and made me feel happy to have made the trip from Phoenix. Thanks, all, for satisfying my craving! I hope tsukemen soon spreads across the US!<//review><pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMWjp-PlJ3S1KBLTCEUMejRxb6q31uhIkXxTHs7=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /pictures><Response>None< /Response>< GmapID>

< userid>
115960942273201366942</userid>
<username>McKay ‚ÄúOnetricked‚Äù Zabriskie</username>< Review>
This place is Cozy and arguably the best Ramen in LA. The Annex is small and easy to miss but it is definitely a hidden gem. There are only about 15-18 seats here  so there is usually a wait, but they take your order and start it so by the time you sit down, your order is almost finished. Be prepared for a little strange smell as you wait.

The Ramen is really high quality and thick. The broth is thick and rich and bursting with flavor. It's goes well with the thick noodles. To top it off, the pork just falls apart in your mouth and makes the experience. I got a soft boiled egg to go with it and it is a must have.

Despite being so busy, the customer service here is as great as could be expected! They always keep your glass full and occasionally check up on you. I highly recommend trying this place at least once. If you don't, you will miss out.</Review>

107063077542687998922< /UserId.>
< username>
Jobie Low<//username>
< date>
1557174550980</date>
<rate>5< /rate>< review>
Visiting LA and friends pointed to Tsujita LA as a must - go for noodles.. When we get there I realize that it serves tsukemen... whaaa..? It's noodles cooked that you dip in the broth. Huh? Why can't we be Slurp-happy and eat ramen?

But tsukemen is a better way to go. You savor the broth-seafood origins that both coats the noodles and becomes a vehicle to taste all the intricacies usually lost while slurping ramen. They want you to try the broth first, then try it with a squeeze of lime, then enjoy with various additions-mine was a a jar of  turnip-like stuff that added heat in a very earthy way. I want to know where I can buy this stuff!

When you're done with the noodles they come around and ask if you want to add broth to your soup. The original soup is very thick, almost undrinkable, but adding broth makes it a very pleasant ending to a great lunch.

The hostess is very nice, sensing we were newbies( it's that obvious?) but explaining how to eat tsukemen for the millionth time in a way that we weren't a bother.

If you go, go early, we walked in at 11amand when we left at11:45 it was like the first showing of Avengers "Endgame." Well worth the first visit, looking forward to the next!</review>

<Text>Would love to give this place a higher review, but honestly, I don't think I could ever give anything more than 3 stars for a wait this long! Nothing is worth waiting hours and hours in line for!!

That being said, their tsukemen definitely is the way to go here. I've had tsukemen at so many other places in LA but nothing tops the unique consistency and taste that you get here.

I like the cheat and halfway through my bowl, I'll just dump the sauce/soup into the bowl of noodles because dipping is hard work! :P

Make sure you are mindful of your parking when you come here as the meters have limits and there are plenty of cops that will come by and enforce them!< /Text><pics>None< /pics>< response>

< review>
I can‚Äôt go back to regular ramen anymore.

I really wish dipping ramen/tsukumen was more popular outside of LA! The intense broth/‚Äúdip‚Äù flavours were perfect for me and my meathead bros. It was like a seafood gravy, and the thick, chewy noodles were so springy they reminded me of jajangmyeon. The ‚Äústages‚Äù of eating it wasn‚Äôt just a gimmick either, it was lightening the flavours so you wouldn‚Äôt feel like death after! ALSO: the soft boiled egg was perfectly boiled, the yolk was legit like liquid gold and just barely settled.

There‚Äôs generally a wait time and no real good area to lounge, but there are plenty of places to check around while you wait. Since it‚Äôs LA, expect to park on the street and pay for the meter (which is actually free on weekends!).

It‚Äôs a lovely different way to enjoy ramen, and probably my favourite way from now on.</review>

<text>Listen. It's worth it. Everything you've ever heard? True and then some. This place most absolutely smacks. The quality that goes into this food will open your eyes and make you realize how blasphemous instant  noodle is.

Now yes, this dipping noodle. I'm an avid ramen lover and didn't necessarily understand the concept behind dipping the noodle. Why not just put it all together and call it ramen?

Well, the broth is actually very flavorful. So flavorful that if you take a spoonful, it's too much to enjoy for long. Dipping the noodle and consuming (slurping is best) immediately after the dip, will be just want you need to enjoy it best. And yes, you should enjoy a couple of noodles and then add the lime. It somehow does an amazing job at subtly attaching itself to the noodle even after being dipped. Top it all off by asking for some extra hot water and you've just enjoyed some of the best noodle you'll ever have.

While here, I ordered the Cha Siu Tsukemen and shared it. It was so good I had to return to order for myself. The second time I still ordered the Cha Siu Tsukemen with extra noodles and extra egg. I regret nothing.

I can't wait to be reunited with this place again.<//text><time>1581124160153<//time><username>Nathaniel Arias-Velez<//username><Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOqcbrIr13gMRPcD4RPXeBGL-cf-5QcyhTIg-Wx=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /Pics><rating>5</rating><resp>None</resp>< gmapID>

<date>1512019518843< /date><rating>3<//rating>< Text>
Been a few times, suffered long waits each time, never been satisfied with the taste. Definitely acquired taste, not your usual Ikkousha, etc for yum. Even Jinya at the Hollywood and Highland mall is far tastier - broth there and Ikkousha are delicious.
11/26/17- Went again with a Japanese from Hokkaido. Ditto for me on the acquired taste - lukewarm dipping noodles, boring broth to dip out in, not enough meat by far. Feel like I just spent $13+ to be fed leftovers. Tons of better tasting ramen shops besides this one. That said, friend immediately noticed the fish flavor in the broth, and being Japanese, liked the dipping noodles. Only downside for her was not enough lemon to squeeze over the noodles.</Text>

<review>First Star: Is the location neat? Yes. The turnover is fast but a staff member is always on hand immediately to clear and wipe tables.

Second Star: Is the staff friendly? Yes.

Third Star: Is the service prompt? Yes. Once you've braved the line outside your food comes quickly. The staff is also conscious of taking orders from those in line to make the service move even quicker. Very efficient.

Fourth Star: Is the product/service satisfactory? Yes. Absolutely. The tsukemen broth is hearty and rich. The cold dipping noodles make a fantastic companion to the hot broth, keeping their springy chew until you're ready to dip. The char siu is tender and full of flavor.

Fifth star: Is the price acceptable? Yes. Always worth it to drop in.<//review>< Resp>

< Text>
See the red chili‚Äôs in the picture. Those chili‚Äôs are just one of the tiny nuances that makes this ramen one of the best. We arrived on a chilly saturday evening to have this ramen and I was pleasantly surprised to see about 30 odd people waiting to get in the restaurant. We opted for patio seating since the wait time was much less in the cold weather. Add 11.50 the ramen is priced reasonably but you do need to add 1.50 soft boiled eggs in order to make this ramen worth it. The broth itself is rich and the pork belly is soft and juicy. The best part about their ramen is that you can get extra broth for free. My girlfriend ended up having the vegan ramen which although tasted a little bit like pho but was worth it for her. Would definitely come back to try the tsukemen.< /Text>

Before my visit, I'd never tried tsukemen and wasn't really a fan of Japanese ramen. However, the ajitama tsukemen here may have changed both of those statements. Well, at least in terms of dipping ramen. I thought the noodles were pleasantly chewy while the broth was thick and not overly salty. The soft-boiled egg and pork were as one would expect from a restaurant that specialized in ramen. My only complaint about the dish was that the broth was a little warmer than room temperature at best, and I'd prefer it to be much hotter. Overall, I left the restaurant feeling satisfied by both the taste and the portion, which is something I'd never experienced before upon finishing a meal at a ramen restaurant.</Text>

Spend the extra dollar and get the tsukemen with the soft boiled egg which was perfectly cooked by Ramen standards. It's expensive for what tsukemen is, but the delicious taste of the soup will have me comming back soon. The soup had these bits of really salty meat which I think went perfectly with the noodles, especially if used sparingly. The soup got cold quick due to the nature of tsukemen so I can't complain about that. It was a bit loud in there on a Thursday night, so i only recomend this place if you want to eat Ramen and nothing else. If you wanna talk to your date or whatever, get it out of your system while you're waiting outside becuase there can be a waiting list when busy. Seating is a bit cramped but I guess if they had less seats then the wait times would be longer. My only complaint is that there isn't more space for this wonderful restaurant to supply the demand for delicious Ramen. I wouldn't call this a traditional Ramen restaurant but I don't think it's what they're going for anyway. They provide a lime to twist over your noodles which is odd but I'm digging it. There's also hand fans at every table which is nice if you start sweating from the hot soup.<//Review>< rate>

< text>
The Tsukmen with Pork is incredibly filling and more salty then I like...although not so salty that I couldn't eat it. I wasn't the only person asking for a to-go container, as it was so filling and too good to leave behind. Staff is super, friendly and willing to explain the menu (there are actual instruction cards at each seat, advising how to eat this traditional food). Lines are long virtually all the time, so be prepared to wait, particularly on the weekends. For the food I'd give 4 starts, but...the entire facility could use a good scrubbing, the tables are sticky and restrooms poorly maintained, hence the 3 stars.< /text>

<user>101955654268357403449< /user>< user_name>
Yutack Kang</user_name>
< date>
1521567237317<//date>
<Rating>5< /Rating><Review>Delicious tsukemen! Service was fast and friendly. Don't hesitate to ask how to eat the tsukemen, the waiters love to help and there's also an instructional sheet for first timers.

Some tips:
1. it's totally fine to slurp, it's actually encouraged
2. if you're looking for spicy, add a spoonful of pickled mustard (karashi takana) onto the noodles. it's very spicy so add only a little at a time
3. You can add the lime at anytime, I like adding it with about a third of the noodles left. This way you can experience the different flavors throughout the meal.
4. Once you're done with your noodles, they'll ask if you want 'wari' (beef broth). This way you can slurp hot broth to complete the meal

Cash only with ATM inside</Review>< Pictures>

<review>There are 2 Tsujita Ramen across each other, the one right at the intersection accept CASH ONLY and the soup not good as the other location across the street. Tsujita Annex is accepting credit card and the broth to me taste better, spicier. Both locations are busy during peak lunch/dinner hours, you could wait in line for 30 mins and longer for a table of 2. The space/table is small, you are literally next to each other and in other face! There are table/booth for larger group otherwise you have to share sitting. Pricey but typical in West LA, expect $15-$20 for each bowl of ramen after tax.< /review><resp>None</resp>< pictures>

<user_id>111950806692932405496<//user_id><Text>My favorite tsukemen in Los Angeles.  The broth is amazing.  It's best to come here after the lunch and dinner rush.  They are open late.</Text><gmapID>0x80c2bb74df48dd81:0xf5e9b108b806741f</gmapID>< pics>

<date>1500308659875<//date><response>None</response>< user_name>
Giancarlo Surla< /user_name>
</record></dataset><record>
< Rate>
5< /Rate>
<text>In my opinion, this is the best place to get ramen in the area--which is really saying something, considering all the options within 20 yards! Simple menu, small interior, and no-fuss service and seating. it's cash only, as well, though there is an ATM in the back, make sure you bring cash if you don't want to pay the fees.

You'll want to be prepared to wait, whether you're there before it opens for lunch/dinner or just walking up. There's always a crowd of people standing outside, and there's a list that has the parties in front of you that you can add your name to. If it's not raining, I would say it doesn't matter at all if you're seated inside or outside. The last couple of times I've been there, the wait has been around half an hour. Your whole party has to be present to be seated.

If you like spicy, the level 3 spicy Tonkatsu is the best! It's a lingering heat, not burning, so you can happily eat through the entire bowl, navigating through an abundant amount of red peppers and green onions. The meat is super tender and flavorful, and the noodles (best purchased "hard" out of all the options!) are firm and taste fresh. I always have trouble picking between that and the Ajitama Tsukemen, which is the dipping ramen--definitely an experience on its own. It comes with thicker noodles and broth than the ramen that comes with the noodles in the broth, and the texture is unbelievable. Extra limes for the noodles are a must, and so is getting the lighter broth at the end to enjoy the entire experience.

Overall such a great spot in a great location. For sure worth the wait, and even though it's super busy you never feel like you're being rushed; great experience with great food every time.< /text><gmapID>0x80c2bb74df48dd81:0xf5e9b108b806741f< /gmapID><Date>1549653759149<//Date><Pictures>None<//Pictures><user_name>Leah Vergel de Dios<//user_name><resp>None<//resp>< UserId.>
114260703412621045091< /UserId.>
</record>
</dataset><record>

This ramen shop I've been wanting to eat at for a long time and finally got a chance. There side soup dip for the noodles is excellent. Noodles is perfect hardness and chewiness. Egg is beautiful, never seen a more beautifully cooked egg. And the char siu is meaty and substantial. Love it! Pro tip, make sure to come early when it opens for no line! Also can get the added broth and its wonderful soup to wash it all down. Yum üòã<//Review>

<Review>The tsukemen is very similar to the ones you will find in Japan. I would describe it as a diluted version of it. Tsukemen dipping sauce is traditionally more pungent and flavorful. The noodles are cooked perfectly but I don't recommend following their instructions about coating your noodles in lime. The lime easily overpowers the dipping sauce. <review>DELICIOUS!! The wait was 20 minutes which is really difficult for me to do because I get hangry. <Resp>None</Resp>< Date>
1530572810193< /Date>
< review>
Legit tsukemen ramen! This will leave you full and satisfied for sure. I used to never enjoy ramen all that much because I'm never full afterwards like I am eating pho...but oh boy, this place is quite the opposite.

We ordered the Tsukemen Ramen with Chaw Siew. They give you a solid amount of thick and perfectly cooked ramen noodles. I'm a sucker for the thick noodles, thin ones just don't do it as much for me. Next to the heaping bowl of noodles is their awesome creamy and rich broth.

With Tsukemen, you dip the noodles into the broth and then consume. The broth isn't meant for you to slurp on like other ramen bowls, which makes this a somewhat fun experience eating. The broth itself has scattered pieces of meat inside amongst other things and very flavorful overall.

The ramen also came with a softboiled egg which is obviously very tasty. We ordered sake on the side as well.

Overall a pretty good place to get yourself a bowl of Tsukemen Ramen and a nice family ambiance inside. Highly recommended! There is apparently also another restaurant that is EXACTLY the same across the street to help with the popularity and wait time.< /review>

<user>115888693284591417815<//user><name>John Robinson< /name>< Time>
1530686092723< /Time>
<rate>3</rate>< text>
Mixed review for me. This was my first experience with Tatsu ramen. The flavor was very good, but the broth was room temperature...once mixed with the cold noodles, it was cold mess. Not a fan.

I also ordered a spicy ramen which was excellent. Piping hot and a wonderful aroma and flavor. Chili peppers added additional heat, but not too much. I ordered a spiciness of 2 out of 3.

Bad part - server spilled a quarter of the piping hot ramen all over my leg. She helped to get napkins and clean her mess, but did not compensate me with a discount or any other offer. Not an ideal way to treat your customers.

All in all, a good noodle house, but nothing out of the ordinary or exciting. Small, cramped quarters without any charm or pizazz.</text>

<rating>5<//rating><Text>Tip before coming here :) It's cash only.
My second time eating here and both experiences were great! You usually have to sign your name and wait, but most people are pretty good about eating and leaving, so, it doesn't take too long for seats to open. I've waited no more than an hour, and it's worth the wait if so! The staff does get busy running around but are always willing to help and with friendly service too. I definitely recommend eating tsukemen with chashuu. So good!! They have a cute illustration that shows you the proper way of eating it and the waiting staff can explain too if you ask. Remember lime in the noodles! Then dip noodles into the broth. I would definitely recommend eating here if you want to try delicious, authentic tsukemen.< /Text><pics>None< /pics>< Resp>

< Review>
Have been meaning to try this place on Sawtelle for some time. Finally bit the bullet and went to Tsujita for my usual Sunday noodle lunch with my girlfriend.  I must say the food was great! I had the spicy pork ramen (have forgotten the official menu listing) and was pleasantly surprised at the firey heat that the level 3 spicyness brought with it. I mean by simply looking at the bowl you would think it were a normal pork ramen bowl, but one spoonful of that broth will let you know that looks can be deceiving. My girlfriend had the tsukemen (sp?), and was very happy with her plate.

Overall, this place is another great addition to the cuisine offered here in Little Osaka/Sawtelle. Be cautious as this restaurant is VERY popular so be prepared to wait if during peak hours. The taste is well worth the wait, and the pricing is fair.  Can't wait to return.< /Review>

<UserId.>118340948866946722024</UserId.><response>None</response>< Pics>
None< /Pics>
< review>
This is the place that introduced me to tsukemen - thick, cold, chewy noodles dipped in gravy-thick hot soup. Oh buddy, this is the good stuff. As I understand it each of their locations features a different style of broth (hence why there is a second restaurant across the street). If I understood my server correctly this location is fish and pork, and the Annex is just pork. Both are amazing (but I do prefer the Annex overall). Slightly more expensive than most ramen-ya but definitely worth it. Blows all of the hipster competitors out of the water. Don't forget to get soup wari when your broth gets low.

Some caveats: Cash only, but has an ATM. No vegetarian options as far as I know.<//review>

<Text>Decent place for ramen. Expect to wait at least 30 mins for a table. Food is served quickly once you sit down. I had the char siu tsukumen. The pork is very soft and tender and the noodles are cooked well. You dunk the noodles into the pork broth and then slurp it up. The broth did a great job warming up the noodles initially, but quickly became luke warm and didn't do so well warming up the noodles after about 5 mins of slurping. The broth is full of flavor, but very concentrated. Once you are done with the noodles, ask the staff to thin out the broth to make it drinkable.< /Text>< Pictures>

<Review>I finally got to try Tsujita! The ramen here is quite delicious. I can't say if its the same, similar, totally off as from the original Tsujita but I did enjoy my meal here. I got the Tsukemen with soft boiled egg (and asked for less salty from reading other reviews) . The broth is VERY oily - it made me feel super full for the rest of the day- I don't recommend eating this often but it definitely is a treat once in awhile. I believe the spicy sauce was what made the broth, mmm my tummy is just dreaming about how delicious it was :) The soft boiled egg wasn't really soft - boiled, I usually like it runny but some people may prefer it the way Tsujita makes it. The wait is long though, definitely be prepared!<//Review><user_name>Annie Lin<//user_name></record>
</dataset><record>
< response>

<user_id>100366113117526980111<//user_id>< Text>
I don't want to overcomplicate this and write a super long review because it's pretty simple: DELICIOUS TSUKEMEN.

Note that Tsujita has two locations pretty much across each other. This is  the ANNEX. Both are great but if you prefer a fattier, richer broth then I highly recommend the ANNEX over the OG location. And yes, the line is equally long for both restaurants.

If you go during off hours, you'll get a chance to avoid the line but if you want to eat during normal lunch/dinner hours, then prepare to wait (like 1-2 hours). Also this place is CA$H only. The menu is pretty simple, highly highly recommend getting the tsukemen. The portion doesn't seem too big but it is really filling, because of that I recommend getting the regular size and then getting an a delicious tuna rice bowl add on :) Taste the broth alone and then add in a generous heaping of the chili and garlic because it tastes sooooooooo good all together. The tsukemen broth is thick, fatty, rich, savory and perfect for dipping your noodles in!

If you're a fan of noodles (especially chewy thicker noodles) then you have to try this place! It's worth the wait.<//Text>

<user_name>Jennifer Lo</user_name><date>1510338496880</date><rating>5</rating><review>Voted number one in LA and it lived up to the hype! The ramen was so good. I ordered the tsukemen and the tuna don. The tsukemen is the dipping noddles where they give you a bowl of thick concentrated broth and you dip eat bite into the broth. The broth had a strong bonito flavor and wasn't overly salty. The noodles were also perfectly chewy. I ordered the tsukemen with the pork slices, but the normal bowls already have pieces of pork mixed into the broth so don't worry about not having meat. After you're finished with your noodles, you can ask for broth to be poured into your bowl in order to drink the tsukemen broth. This is one of the best bowls that I have had! It's alway great because it is open till late night!< /review>< Pics>

<user_id>105138695150861112121< /user_id><gmapID>0x80c2bb74df48dd81:0xf5e9b108b806741f<//gmapID><Time>1486020304002< /Time>< Review>
Awesome joint for Tsukemen aka dipping ramen. You can add wari (extra broth) at the end for free. Table condiments are fresh garlic and chili flakes. In my person opinion, this place has a low noise level, which is great if you want to focus on the delicious bowl of noodles and watch the chef's expertly prepare them. No distractions, basically! The flavor of the broth and bite to the noodle will make you come back. Many ramen shops serve Tsukemen, but Tsujita sets the standard. Try their other locations for broth variations and table condiment variations. Other locations also have full menus with plenty of delicious Japanese options.<//Review>

Over the past year, I've been trying all the Ramen on the west side I can. This is hands down, the best char siu ramen I've had. I am hesitant to say this, as there is limited seating, and this could only increase the amount of people eating here.

<userid>100941150984364933877</userid><Name>Vivian Sam< /Name><Time>1451410087782<//Time>< rating>

< Text>
I love their noodles here. They aren't the typically skinny ramen style, they're plump almost like Udon. I always order the ramen with or without extra char siu. The broth is heavy and flavorful. The red seasoning is very addicting. The wait is always crazy. However, I do appreciate the staff taking your order before you get seated so you get your food shortly after being seated. <UserId.>111694869338945346346<//UserId.><user_name>Nick Degani</user_name>< Time>
1476368126524<//Time>
<rating>4< /rating>< text>
If you're tired of Shinsengumi or Daikokuya, give Tsujita a try. For starters it's dipping noodles rather than traditional soup noodle. Do mind the line though; I'd recommend coming at non peak hours... Or if you have immense luck, come whenever.

So it's simple, come in, order the Tsukemen as that's what they're known for. The dipping broth and ramen come in separate bowls and may confuse you initially but take a look at the eating instruction manuel if it's your first time here or ask a waiter. Get extra limes and apply to the broth as needed. I enjoyed the ramen texture and the broth but be prepared for an oily broth. The meat was wonderfully made and practically melts in your mouth.

So the experience is probably novel for most people but it's definitely worth trying. The ramen is a little more on the expensive side though, and the broth cools down pretty quickly so it's best to eat as soon as you get your food. Cold ramen with cold broth is not pleasant at all. Oh and Tsujita is cash only so be prepared for that.</text>

< Text>
This is for sure my favorite ramen shop! The complexity of the broth is out of this world! Perfectly balanced, it is truly sensational. Its served tsukemen style which is when the noodles come separate from the soup.

The broth is rich, fatty, spicy and is loaded with garlic. The noodles are thicker than standard ramen noodles. They are similar to udon but with the bite and texture of a ramen noodle.

If you want to know how this stands up to ramen in Japan, I can honestly say this is as good as the best places over there. I recently visited and made sure to eat ramen all over the country and Tsujita is as good as any of them. I have also taken many Japanese friends here and they confirm it's greatness!<//Text>

< review>
Every time when I go to LA, this is a MUST GO place for me! Guys, if you like ramen, you should come here and TRY! I like their Tsukemen! It's my first time having ramen with the noodles on a bowl and the soup on the other. It makes the noodles less soggy when we eat.

Talking about the Tsukemen, the soup is really strong and rich, which is a good thing. But last time when I went there, the soup was a bit too salty, but other than that, everything was PERFECT! The overall presentation is nice and I like the idea that they have one big piece of fried seaweed on the noodles bowl, which is perfect for a person like me, since I don't really like to dip the whole seaweed into the soup.

I will definitely try their other ramen next time when I visit LA!< /review>

<Rate>5< /Rate><gmapID>0x80c2bb74df48dd81:0xf5e9b108b806741f</gmapID><pictures>None</pictures>< review>
Alright so I've been hearing how everyone says this is the best ramen in LA.  I had to find out for myself.  Yes, I got the tsukemen ramen with charsiu.  You have 3 different stages to eat the ramen.  First stage is just dipping about 1/3 of your ramen into the broth and eating it.  The second stage is to squeeze lime into your ramen and finishing your noodles.  The final stage is adding the soup wari into your broth. </record>
</dataset><record>
<Text>The hard ramen was wet and juicy, wasn't loosy goosey. Service was wack, never comin' back.< /Text><GmapID>0x80c2bb74df48dd81:0xf5e9b108b806741f< /GmapID><username>James Nguyen<//username>< user_id>
100848537494120969815<//user_id>
< date>
1469520421466</date>
<resp>None< /resp>< Pictures>
None</Pictures>
< rating>
2<//rating>
</record></dataset><record>
< time>
1447657329076<//time>
< Text>
If you Google search "best Ramen in Los Angeles" a great many lists and opinions will point toward Tsujita. The Tsujita Noodles Annex resides just across the street from Tsujita proper with a more limited menu, sticking only to the ramen and tsukemen that people clamor for.

I wanted to love the Annex. As a fan of good Japanese ramen, I felt no need to venture further west than Little Tokyo, but no longer could I ignore the much publicized Tsujita. Once you get to the Annex, you walk up, sign your name on the list and begin the wait. After about a half an hour, our order was taken, and another half an hour later, our name was being called to take our seat in the restaurant. The most notable experience when walking into the Annex is the smell. I wish it was a pleasant one, however, it was, for lack of a better term, funky......something like dead animal, stinky feet, and cheetos. Apparently, it is the slow drawing out of all the lovely flavors that go into the broth that brings out this smell.

Being that our order had been placed long before, our ramen was out shortly after being seated. The ramen came, a heaping serving of bean sprouts atop. Traditionally, I like to dive into the broth before anything else when eating ramen. After doing so, I had nothing else to think but, "this tastes like liquid fat." It's definitely flavorful, but as fatty and salty as could be. Once you mix everything together, char siu, bean sprouts, noodles, etc., you see how it all works together, but alone, the broth is impossible to enjoy. Unfortunately, there were a couple other issues. The additions to the ramen were cold. Obviously the bean sprouts were cold, but the char siu and egg were also, which created an odd experience.

In the end, I can appreciate the authenticity of Tsujita's ramen, but it has not persuaded me to move away from Daikokuya.< /Text>

< Review>
Tsujita LA is the most fascinating ramen place I've been to.  For one, they only serve ramen in this particular restaurant at lunch time (11am-2pm) and you should expect a line if you don't come a little before it opens.  The ramen here is very milky and heavy compared to the other choices around.  Some people will not like it because it really bogs down in your stomach but the flavor feels absolutely delicious and the noodles are just the right size.  All-in-all, a great choice for more experience ramen adventurers.  (Expect to pay around $10 along with the ability to slightly add more ingredients).  There are also some other noodle options that I didn't have a chance to explore.

Parking-wise, as usual in this area, look around the neighborhood nearby or on the street.</Review>

< review>
I watched a documentary on Netflix where they had Tsukemen in Tokyo and I immediately wanted to have some. There's no other place in LA that's better known for their Tsukemen than Tsujita so my boyfriend and I made our way to Sawtelle in crazy traffic just to sample some.

I had heard that the wait on weekends can be pretty bad here and I can see why. The place is tiny. They did open the Tsujita Annex diagonally across the street but I have yet to peek in there. Since it was a weekday, we were able to grab the last 2 spots at the counter.

I had the Tsukemen while my boyfriend had the char siu ramen. I didn't care for the broth on their regular ramen too much. I prefer richer darker broth.

As for the Tsukemen, when I had the first bite, I was a little overwhelmed by the intense bonito flavor of the broth. It was very seafood-y. However, after I added lime to the noodle as recommended, the flavor balanced out extremely well. I thoroughly enjoyed my ramen to the last bite.

The restaurant is cash only. Parking used to be a pain but they have free valet parking with validation now. It's located behind the building.<//review>

<Rating>4<//Rating>< text>
First things first, you gotta know that the broth of the tsukemen and ramen is different than that of the Annex across the street. Lines are long, so I don't recommend going with a group bigger than 3. I went with a group of 8 and ended up waiting for 45 minutes even though our wait time was estimated to be only 20.

If you're coming here, try the tsukemen. The broth is more of a sauce that you dip the bouncy thick al dente noodles in. Get the 2nd option with the seasoned soft boiled egg. Squeeze the limes onto the soup to combat the dense fishy broth. At the end, ask for more broth (the actual soup) to dilute the dense sauce. Bring it home, and buy some ramen noodles from Nijiya to have yourself another meal ;)

I've tried the ramen, as well as the dons and I have to say that nothing compares to the tsukemen. The ramen broth was alright, but I hate the thin noodles that they use. I want my noodles to have a bite to them! The dons (Rice bowls) are $4 if you add them onto your entree, $6 otherwise.

How this differs from Annex: I can't finish a bowl of tsukemen because of how intensely fishy the broth is. I have as many friends who disagree and don't taste the fishiness as those who agree with my sentiments. I say taste the tsukemen from both restaurants. You can't go wrong with Tsujita!</text>

117371214850934387732< /user>

< text>
Before you walk in the door, take note of the odor that exudes from this establishment. It's a mixture of dirty gym socks and old wet clothes that haven't been transferred to the dryer for weeks. The rancid smell did not go unnoticed, but based on the Yelp reviews, we assumed that the smell must be coming from elsewhere, so we proceeded with caution.

They have two main Ramin options here - Tsukemen and Tonkotsu. The latter, the Tonkotsu, is a "specialty broth" that they make in house. There were four of us at dinner, three of us ordered a version of the Tonkotsu.

When the food arrived, the putrid smell overtook our table. Giving them the benefit of the doubt, I tasted the soup; however, it tasted just as badly as it smelled.

I knew immediately that I wasn't interested in eating another bite. When we politely requested an exchange, the manager, Shanon, was called over by our waitress. He rudely told me that they didn't offer any "refunds or exchanges." I explained this wasn't a refund, because I had not eaten the soup. It was literally unstirred, chives still sitting on top of the rotten broth. After arguing for a few minutes with the manager, he was unwilling to remove this item from our bill. We paid for the items that were eaten with cash and proceeded to walk out the of the restaurant. We were literally chased out by the manager, telling us the cops were called and that we had to wait. This manager, Shanon, got in our face, tried to take picture of us on his cell phone, and stood behind our car so we couldn't leave. It was a frightening and appalling experience for four young girls.

I would never recommend this restaurant to anyone. If you read many of the one-star reviews below, they all have the same thing in common, the disgusting odor. The service was so bad, that I would personally rather pay for you to eat lunch anywhere but here.

PS. I attended this establishment with a friend who is 50% Japanese, who had enjoyed Ramin countless times before. She too agreed the Ramin was inedible.< /text>

My all time favorite ramen spot. </record></dataset><record>
< Rating>
5</Rating>
<Review>The best tsukemen I've ever had and some of the best ramen noodles in LA.

I always walk by this corner and see a ridiculous line at lunch (they only serve ramen at lunch). I was extra hungry and took my lunch break at 12:45 instead of 1 and there happened to be a free seat at the ramen bar so I knew this was an opportunity I couldn't pass up.

They have two options for ramen: Tsukemen (dipping) and traditional tonkotsu. From there you can choose chashu pork, no meat, eggs, etc. They also have some other rice dishes, but this artisan noodle stand is famous for the ramen so I went with the Chashu tsukemen.

My order came out quickly- they gave a generous portion of noodles and pork and a bowl of thick, saucey broth with a salty and perfectly gooey egg, bamboo shoots, and some pieces of meat. They also give you free lime and you can customize your broth with ginger, spice, tonkotsu sauce, and tsukemen sauce. The ramen was thick like spaghetti, firm and a little chilled. At first I dipped the noodles in the broth too long and it was way too salty. After swiftly swishing the noodles, I found the perfect balance between noodles and soup. The broth tasted even better after I ground some sesame seeds and added a little lime and tonkotsu sauce. The broth is what makes this place stand out from other ramen stands: they brew it for 60 hours with a wide variety of flavors that all combine to create an amazing savory sensation.

My only complaint is the price, a bowl of chashu tsukemen will run $15 without tip, but I was very satisfied with my meal and extra noodles and soup are only $1.50. Cash only. This place does live up to its hype and is simply a great ramen stand.</Review><pics>None</pics>< date>
1431234737093</date>

<Time>1426113178090</Time><Review>A much-belated review: After being thwarted at the regular Tsujita (they were closed filming a TV show or something) I noticed the Annex across the street and thought I'd give it a shot. I didn't even know this place existed, but I'm so glad I it was there! It was around 2pm-ish so the wait was minimal, thank goodness--I guess it can get kind of nutty, judging from the other reviews. It's a small but comfortable place, with clean modern (but not sterile) decor. I was a little surprised upon reading the menu--it was a lot more Chinese-influenced than what I was expecting. I got the regular ramen with the soft boiled egg and the Ikura (salmon roe) bowl. I was intrigued by the Tsukemen but wasn't in the mood for it at that moment. This ramen is definitely different than the standard Japanese ramen--it's much more bold and rich, with thick, curly, chewy noodles--yum! I can see why maybe some people wouldn't care for it, but it suited my Korean palate very well, especially with extra garlic and spicy seasonings. The Ikura bowl was good, with fresh roe and rice. Nothing mind-blowing but exactly what I was expecting so it satisfied. I was very full at the end of the meal, but knew I wanted to come back sooner than later. I need to try the tsukemen next time!</Review>< user_id>

<date>1426272428195< /date>< review>
Pros:
- creamy broth (so rich so delicious)
- dipping noodles for dinner (I think the original Tsujita only has this for lunch)
- tonkatsu ramen (I liked it better than the dipping ramen)

Cons:
- tiny tiny tiny restaurant means long wait for seating
- difficult to find parking
- pricey, especially if you choose add-ons (egg, green onions, seaweed, etc.)

Bottom line: I believe that a good bowl of ramen should be hearty and include an egg and other garnishings. If it's your first time, and you're feeling adventurous for tsukemen, try to get your friend to order tonkatsu ramen just in case you don't like the dipping style. That's how I ended up eating all of my dad's tonkatsu ramen and none of my dipping ramen...<//review>

<pictures>None</pictures><Date>1425063211899</Date>< Rate>

<Text>*Thumbs up*
After a 2-hour sweaty hike at Peters Canyon, my wife and I made the 1-hour long drive to LA just to have ramen here. It was definitely a spontaneous thing, because I was craving ramen and I kept seeing Tsujita popping up in reviews.

Luckily we got to Tsujita just shortly after the 11am opening time, because by the time we left the place was crawling with people waiting outside. Of course, I had to have the $14 bowl of tsukemen... and for my first time, it was pretty awesome. Having the two separate bowls was a bit odd at first, but it came natural after a few slurps and honestly it made the ramen eating experience that much more fun.

Both the noodles are broth are #1 in my book, thus far. The noodles had a great chew and consistency, and just perfectly sucked up the broth. The broth is very thick (viscous is the fancy word being thrown around) and heavily concentrated in flavor. Although it was mostly pork based, the broth is just so heavy that the lime squeeze on the noodle is essential to cut through it all.

The chashu is more of the thick cut variety with the layers of white fat still visible. I thought it tasted great, especially after dipping it in the broth. The neon orange, ooey gooey yolk from the egg was just #yolkporn at its finest. Yes, that was a hashtag.

*Thumbs down*
Yep, $14 for a bowl of ramen is pretty darn high and I think the highest I've ever paid for a bowl of ramen. I think this tsukemen is fine for the occasional splurge. Taking it easy on the arteries and the wallet, I can't imagine eating it on a regular basis. Cash only is irksome -- it's not like this place is dirt cheap. They need to get with the times and accept credit card.<//Text><userid>110742205096982467567< /userid>< GmapID>
0x80c2bb74df48dd81:0xf5e9b108b806741f<//GmapID>
</record>
</dataset><record>
<userid>110297995237040771742< /userid><user_name>Vivian Hoang</user_name><date>1418061928879< /date><Rate>5< /Rate><review>Visiting from the Bay area where most ramen places are just decent, I had very high expectations for Tsujita. The wait wasn't bad, about 30-45 mins on a Sunday afternoon. The shops around the area are fun to browse while you're waiting.

My friend and I both tried the tonkatsu ramen. OMG dat broth. So fatty, sooo GOOD. The char siu was also amazingly tender and delicious. The only con was the egg was a little overcooked. But I'll overlook that in this case, since the rest of the bowl was pure perfection. Best ramen I've had so far.

I will definitely be back, especially to try the Tsukemen next time!

Service was great. CASH only!</review><pics>None< /pics>< Response>

<userid>100934048083327874295</userid><name>Muy S</name><time>1398929446561</time>< resp>
None<//resp>
<pics>None<//pics>< text>
This restaurant is a must if you are in the area for lunch, as they only serve the tsukemen ramen for lunch.

Get the tsukemen ramen with char siu pork! (I think it was $14. worth it!)

It comes with two bowls:
- one bowl with thick cold noodles, seaweed, lime, and thick slices of pork
- one bowl of thick broth with chunks of pork and the hidden treasure boiled egg ;)

I first took a sip of the broth.  It was very salty o_o
BUT... once you squeeze some lime on the noodles, dip some noodles in the broth then pull them out, it is so delicious :O !!!!

Despite what it looks like, it is a heavy meal.  The noodles are soooo good!  They have the right thickness so that when they are coated with the rich broth, the balance of salt and acidity with the lime is perfect.  The lime adds some freshness to the meal.

The pork slices are thick, and you really feel like you're getting a lot of meat with your meal.  My friend ordered extra char siu because he thought it would not be enough... but it was definitely enough meat without the extra plate.  Plus there's chunks of meat in the broth already!

Last but not least... beautiful egg.  I love you, egg.

PS: Line gets long.  Park in the residential streets.. or valet is available too.< /text>

<UserId.>109970605133245577901<//UserId.>< name>
Victor J Garza< /name>
<Date>1414185233694<//Date>< Rate>
4<//Rate>
< review>
I recently went to Tsujita for the first time as per a friends recommendation. The main feature of this place, as the name suggests is its noodles. As my friend informes me, they are now serve noodles every evening, which apparently they weren't before. What I had was the Tsukemen style ramen which is noodles on the side and ramen broth on a separate bowl for dipping the noodles into. The noodles are served cold and the broth hot. Because the noodles are cold, the broth eventually cools down. Unlike hot cooked noodles served in the magma hot broth, these noodles aren't crazy hot, so they are generally great in any weather, where's the magma hot ramen is more desirable during cold days, though not that hot weather stops me from eating any kind of ramen.
Over all, the noodles were good, the broth was thick and rich. I will definitely Tsujita again. Waits can be long, so be prepared.< /review>

< text>
The Best Place to get Tsukemen in LA! I promise! :)

After my trip to Japan, I've realized that this is as close as you can get to authentic tsukemen. If you never had it before, you're in for a treat. Tsukemen is basically just dipping noodles. You get a bowl of thick noodles where you dip into a bowl of thick pork broth. So good!

They even have a step-by-step menu that describes how to properly eat your tsukemen.

Order the Char Siu Tsukemen ($13.95) and you will not be disappointed. You get 5 big pieces of char siu. The portions are pretty big and I can never finish a bowl.

I love coming here on the weekdays because the wait is shorter than the crazy long lines you see on the weekends.

FYI, you can only order it during lunch-time. And it's cash only.</text>

< review>
Living in the South Bay, I'm spoiled by all of the great ramen places a short drive away. I heard great things about Tsujita LA, so I made the trek to West LA and it was well worth the drive. I ordered the ajitama tsukemen, which was the best iteration of this dish that I have tried. The noodles had the perfect texture and the broth was rich and deep with pork and umami goodness. The egg was cooked to a perfect soft-medium. I tasted some of the tonkotsu ramen that my friend ordered and I can say the broth is one of the best I have tried. It has a deep pork flavor with a subtle sweetness that takes it over the top. If you love ramen, this destination has to be on your short list.< /review>
